We define $r(t)$ to be the radius (in {[}mm{]}) of the area $A(t)$ (in
{[}mm\textsuperscript{2}{]}) at time $t$. Then the circumference of $A$
is $C=2\pi r$ and we know that

\begin{align*}\frac{dA}{dt} = k\cdot C = k\cdot 2\pi r(t).\end{align*}

The area $A$ expressed in terms of $r$ is $A=r^2\pi$. We take the
derivative on both sides and get

\begin{align*}\frac{d}{dt}A = \frac{d}{dt}(r^2\pi) = 2r(t) \frac{dr}{dt}\pi.\end{align*}

We combine the two equations $dA/dt = 2k\pi r(t)$ and
$dA/dt = 2r(t)dr/dt \pi$ above and cancel $2\pi r(t)$ to get

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \frac{dr}{dt} = k.\end{align*}

Integrating leads to

\begin{align*}r(t)\ = kt + const.\end{align*}

To find $A(t)$ again we get back to the formula

\begin{align*}A(t)\ = r(t)^2\pi = (kt+const)^2\pi.\end{align*}

Now all that's left to do is find the constants $k$ and $const$. For
that we use the information given\begin{align*}A(t)=1.\end{align*} So, we get

\begin{align*}A(0)= (k\cdot 0 + const)^2\pi = const^2\pi = 1,\end{align*}

which leads to

\begin{align*}\displaystyle const =\frac{1}{\sqrt\pi}.\end{align*}

The unit of constant is {[}mm{]}. We can take the positive solution of
the root, since negative numbers don't make sense in this context. Now
we use

\begin{align*}A(1) = \left(1 \cdot k + \frac{1}{\sqrt\pi}\right)^2\pi = 2,\end{align*}

which gives

\begin{align*}k = \frac{(\sqrt2-1)}{\sqrt\pi}.\end{align*}

The unit of \emph{k} is {[}mm/day{]}.

Hence, the final equation for $A(t)$ is given by

\begin{align*}A(t) = \left(\frac{(\sqrt2-1)}{\sqrt\pi}t + \frac{1}{\sqrt\pi}\right)^2\pi,\end{align*}

which you can simplify to

\begin{align*}A(t) = \left((\sqrt2-1)t + 1\right)^2.\end{align*}
